---
title: "Economic stagnation in Switzerland: discussion of a growing debate"
author: "Celâl Güney"
format: html
editor: visual
---


In the last years, recurring debates are emerging in Switzerland regarding the future of the country's socio-economic model, showing a rising concern by the Swiss elites for their country's economic performance. One of the most growing debates is about economic growth: does Switzerland, as in other Western countries, suffer from economic slow-down, or even stagnation ? This was suggested in an article published in 2022 by the renown Swiss-German newspaper *Neue Zürcher Zeitung*. This article, written by Thomas Fuster and entitled *"Immigration: The Swiss economy is primarily growing extensively"* argued that the Swiss economy is growing "extensively", that is, only thanks to demographic growth and hence immigration. While economic growth, measured by the famous domestic product (GDP), is still growing due to immigration, GDP per capita growth remains near-stagnant because of the decline in productivity growth. This article provoked heated reactions among the neoliberal think thank *Avenir Suisse* and the business interest association *EconomieSuisse*, which responded through a series of articles offering an overview and a discussion of the performance of the Swiss economy in the last decades. Both EconomieSuisse and Avenir Suisse were eager to prove that Switzerland's economy is resilient, that extensive growth is still a fact, and that the country still hold its privileged position as the Swiss miracle.






